There’s a long wait, but you finally get a table and order drinks. The night's special is an expensive, complicated cocktail that sounds right up your alley. A few minutes later your drinks arrive — each accompanied by a paper straw. Within minutes, the straw is limp and soggy. But at least you’re fighting climate change, right? In actuality, the solution to climate change isn’t quite that easy. Plastic straw waste accounts for less and 1% of all plastic waste entering the ocean every year. Additionally, only 100 fossil fuel companies are responsible for 70% of the world’s total greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. The amount that a single household, let alone a single person, contributes to GHG emissions is miniscule compared to what is created by large corporations. Realistically, fossil fuel companies would have to be held accountable to significantly curb climate change. But accountability isn’t profitable in the short term, so these companies decided to manipulate the narrative instead. They want you to think it’s your problem to fix. However, this doesn’t necessarily mean that all the recycling, electric vehicles, and paper straws are useless. Consumer demand is part of the problem. We have little control over what fuel is available to us, but we can still try to take positive steps in other ways. Climate-conscious consumer behavior could shift entire industries toward more sustainable practices. And from a psychological perspective, framing the climate change narrative as personal seems to make people more receptive to policy changes to curb climate change. From an ethical perspective, taking individual actions against climate change, like avoiding unnecessary driving, can be part of a larger harm reduction strategy. Though individual actions will not be able to solve the climate crisis on its own, we shouldn’t let perfect impede progress. Climate change deniers and climate change believers both have their own moral reasonings and beliefs to back their stances, but one thing they have in common is their concern for the economy. So talk to them about climate change's effect on the economy. In particular, one thing that motivates many climate change deniers are their own investments in the fossil fuel industry. A similar concern that is more common for the average person is the price and efficiency of renewable energy. But energy costs won't improve as climate change progresses. Although renewable energy is getting significantly cheaper, the initial switch is still costly. Until it is streamlined, there will be challenges that come with buying electric cars or having solar panels, like finding a charging station or living somewhere with little sunlight. These are just a few reasons people may want to stick with fossil fuels, and denying climate change makes it easier to do so. Pro-climate change conversations also focus greatly on the economy, but for different reasons. Climate change believers recognize the catastrophic possibilities that may occur if things continue to get worse. They believe the disasters that come from climate change, like severe weather, will stunt global development and increase poverty rates, which in turn negatively impact the economy. Therefore, they believe the best way to save the economy is to switch to renewable energy, change the direction we are moving in, and create a better, more sustainable future. Furthermore, they believe that switching to renewable energy will pay off in the long run for the economy and can be the cheapest source of energy. In this way, economic appeals can be used for a wide range of audiences. [[How can renewable energy save the economy?]] [[Do economic appeals really convince conservative voters?]] Taylor, M. (2014). World Wildlife Fund.Motivational Interviewing (MI) is a set of conversational techniques that are designed to help an individual, or team, guide someone through the process of resolving an unwanted behavior and/or belief. The practice of MI is based in effective communication and is aimed towards establishing a connection with the person undergoing 'treatment.' It is therefore meant to be customized to the context of the encounter, allowing MI to be generalizable to many beliefs, including those pertaining to climate change. There are four principles that describe the general process of resolving a person’s resistance to change using MI. First, you must develop and express empathy to the person through the process of getting to know them. In most situations, including climate change, this could be in the form of trying to understand how the person’s background has led them to, and enforces, their ideas. You then aim to help the person recognize any discrepancies between their thoughts and actions. For example, in persuading someone against climate inaction, you could help them recognize how their fondness for clean drinking water can be directly impacted by environmentally harmful policies of their local government. During the MI encounter, the third principle reminds the interviewer to roll with resistance from the person, understanding that change can be a gradual, and lengthy, process. The final principle of MI aims to make the change in their behavior and/or beliefs permanent by teaching the practitioner to support the person’s self-efficacy, or ability to continue through the process of making the change on their own. The use of MI has been reported to be effective in moving people away from their denial of climate change when used in a clinical setting. While interactions in day-to-day life would be of a significantly different form than what can be used in a clinical setting, its guiding principles can help us improve how we engage with others. From a broad perspective, MI is a means of giving us the context to guide a person through change while also providing us the mental space to handle their potential failure to do so. (link:"Strategies for Clinical Discussions About Climate Change.")[(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.7326/M20-6443")] Annals of Internal Medicine, 174(3), 417–418.Unlike many other science topics, political position plays a major role in a person’s beliefs and attitudes about climate change. In America, Democrats and liberal-leaning individuals are more likely than Republicans and conservative-leaning people to believe the Earth is warming, that the warming is being caused by humans, that the warming is serious, and that there is scientific consensus about the warming. These differences are stark with 71% of Democrats believing in the human causes of climate change and only 27% of Republicans believing this. (link:"Not all science topics follow this pattern! Check out some tables on other divisive science topics to see the partisan split!")[(go-to-url:"https://www.pewresearch.org/politics/2009/07/09/section-5-evolution-climate-change-and-other-issues/")] Party lines are not the only things that impact climate change belief. Levels of education also impact beliefs on climate change, but in opposite ways for the political spectrum. For liberals, worry about climate change increases with an increase in education, while worry about climate change decreases with an increase in education for conservatives. This difference is more prevalent in the United States than in Europe. Despite slightly different attitudes towards climate change, most Europeans believe in the human causes of climate change while less than half of Americans do. The polarization in beliefs between the parties is mostly seen when asked these direct types of questions like, “Is climate change real?” or “Are humans causing climate change?”. That said, there is agreement in the smaller, and more actionable, aspects of climate change. The majority of Americans (both Democrat and Republican) support expanding alternative energies such as solar and wind. Majorities of both parties trust climate scientists at least a moderate amount and say climate scientists should have a major role in the creation of climate policy. When issues related to climate change are framed in a non-climate way, they are more likely to be supported by all people regardless of political leaning. Democrats and Republicans are equally likely to actually live in a way that is environmentally conscious, though neither party is very likely to take many steps towards living more sustainably (typical Americans). Global Environmental Change, 23(5), 1009-1017. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2013.04.001One of the best ways to teach people about climate change, despite misinformation and climate change denial, is humor. Humor takes many forms and lowers people’s defenses. In other words, making funny jokes about climate change can make even climate change deniers feel at ease so that some real scientific information might get through. Research shows that this occurs because humor helps climate change activists "meet people where they are," by connecting to their everyday lives. Humor also allows scientists to indirectly discuss climate change with uninformed people. This makes them more receptive than they would be to direct arguments that their opinions are wrong. In some ways, this approach is like dangling scientific information as a carrot on a stick rather than shoving it down someone’s throat. The latter approach could make even receptive people reject the information, whereas the former makes it seem almost like "biting" on the information was their idea to begin with. Humans think differently from farm animals, of course, but the similarities are often striking… By helping people understand and digest climate change science more easily, humor is an excellent tool that scientists can use to spread awareness of climate change and stamp out misinformation. (link:"A Laughing matter? Confronting climate change through humor.") [(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.polgeo.2018.09.006")] Political Geography, 68, 154–163. 4. Becker, A., & Anderson, A. A. (2019). (link: "Using humor to engage the public on climate change: the effect of exposure to one-sided vs. two-sided satire on message discounting, elaboration and counterarguing.")[(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.22323/2.18040207")] Journal of Science Communication, 18(04), A07.Conversations can use different communication appeals, which can have impacts on how information is received, shared, accepted/declined, and understood. One common communication appeal that is used in climate change conversations is the guilt appeal (making someone feel guilty), which is used to either defend or argue against climate change. Guilt is a person’s emotional response to a flaw in their standards of conduct. When people feel guilty, they typically feel morally forced to correct their actions or behaviors; when taking climate change into account, guilt appeals try to make someone change their actions to be environmentally friendly. The major problem with guilt appeals is that they can easily annoy people if there is a direct reason to affect a person’s attitude; as a result, guilt appeals in climate change talks do not always motivate people to make environmentally friendly changes to their behaviors or actions. Guilt appeals can be a less useful strategy for climate change communication compared to some of the other appeals, such as humor. [[Go back and play again->Starting Passage]], try some different tactics!] ]] |==|Combating climate change requires alterations in human behavior to lower carbon emissions. Fear appeals draw on strong emotions in attempt to cause such behavioral changes. The emotion linked with climate fear has been given the label of “eco-anxiety”. While practical anxiety has been shown to have positive effects on behavior alterations, there is a fine line between a practical and over-emotional response. Trying to elicit such a practical response has been the reason fear appeals have become so common. With the goal of causing a practical and positive change, climate change advertisements attempt to use fear as a motivational driver. This method can often result in the opposite effect than intended. Surveys have found that fear appeals did not change behaviors on climate change. Instead, the level of anxiety associated with fear appeals led to inaction on the topic. Additionally, fear appeals have been shown to cause higher levels of distrust. The negative effects of fear appeals have been shown to have a rebound effect on the behaviors of their audience. Balancing between the inclusion of enough information to create practical change while not inducing fear has been a challenge. Recent models have shown that framing a fear appeal with an end goal increased willingness for change. Improving fear appeals could lead to significant change and impact climate change over time. While end goal framing could be an effecitve approach in the future, current fear appeal methods are not effective. Want to see how you did, and learn how to get better?->The End]]Some religions, such as Taoism, are actually opposed to climate change adaptations. This is simply because Taoism does not encourage its believers to convince others or be too pushy on individual subjects. Therefore, Taoist follows would not typically be as receptive to climate change adaptations because it is not within their best interests to try to push different agendas nor have agendas pushed onto them. However, does this necessarily mean that those who practice Taoism do not believe in climate change or making climate adaptations? No. Taoism mostly contains concepts that relate to care of the natural world. This includes plants, water, land, insects and animals. Taosim practices in more recent times have even started to become aware of concepts such as the carbon footprint and how to reduce their footprints by reducing the use of insense or firecrackers. Perhaps we should all learn lessons from Taoism and learn to be more Tao-erlant of the environment. Environment: Science and Policy for Sustainable Development, 46(10), 32-46.Eco-anxiety is a term used to describe an emotional state of a person when talking about ecological crises. Climate change is an ecological crisis. Climate change generates specific emotions when discussed using certain words and phrases. Fear appeals create higher levels of anxiety within a person. Eco-anxiety is an appropriate term when used to discuss the reactions people may have. They have increased anxiety over ecological issues, thus "eco-anxiety". (2022) (link: "Eco-anxiety: What it is and why it matters")[(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.3389/fpsyg.2022.981814")] Frontiers in PsychologyEnd-goal framing is discussing a topic using terminal factors which motivate a person. For climate change, fear appeals only cause hopelessness and inaction making them ineffective. Recent studies have shown that goal framing methods were able to change carbon lowering behaviors of households. Pairing a fear appeal with a positive end-goal such as a better environment could be helpful when fear appeals are being used. It can create hope and generate more action to avoid climate change. This strategy would be better than just a fear appeal alone. While many studies have looked at goal framing, few studies have analyzed their current use with fear appeals against climate change. The study terminology and methods used for climate change goal framing have also been inconsistent. There needs to be more comparative research on the effectiveness of goal framed fear appeals versus a fear appeal alone. Want some tips on setting goals for yourself? (2020) (link: "Framing climate change for effective communication: a systematic map") [(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.1088/1748-9326/aba4c7")] Environmental Research LettersResearch shows that most people respond well to climate change jokes, but humor can have negative effects as well. Numerous studies have shown that humor effectively improves audience perceptions, awareness, and knowledge regarding climate change. One of the many reasons for this is that humor is extremely effective in getting people to lower their defenses because it broaches the issue outside of the context of politics and polarization. However, sometimes humor lowers audience defenses too much. Studies have shown that sometimes framing climate change in a humorous context can make it seem like climate change is not a serious issue, or reduce the audience’s perception of risk and fear, which can decrease intentions to take action to prevent it—laughing while protesting can be tricky! From that perspective, it is true that humor around climate change can be both good and bad. Very few studies have compared how well climate change jokes work on different audiences. However, some studies focused on a specific audience. They found that humor is particularly effective in engaging and informing lower-educated audiences. Some examples include dairy farmers and fishermen, who tend to be less educated. Those studies concluded that less educated people have a hard time accessing and understanding scientific information. They have an easier time understanding climate change when they learn about it through comedy. A 2017 study where the authors produced articles on climate change with and without humor found that humor is not a very effective approach in scientific articles about climate change. They posited that humor can trivialize the issue, which can upset scientific readers. It is very important to consider the audience of climate change messages to know how best to speak to them. (link: "Are audiences receptive to humour in popular science articles? An exploratory study using articles on environmental issues.")[(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.22323/2.16040201")] Journal of Science Communication, 16(4), 1–15.Renewable energy will not magically save the economy all on its own, but there are plenty of ways in which it can significantly improve the economy. For example, solar farms in the U.S. can earn as much as $40,000 per year for every Megawatt installed, and the profit margin is 10-20% depending on environmental factors. If we switch to renewable energy as our main source of fuel, the industry can grow within the country, and we won't have to rely on importing fossil fuels from other nations. Money spent on renewable energy will go right back into our own economy instead of going to other countries. ''References:'' Finance & Development Magazine. (2019). [(go-to-url: "https://8billiontrees.com/solar-panels/solar-farm-income-per-acre/")] 8 Billion Trees: Carbon Offset Projects &amp; Ecological FootprintResearch shows that many psychological factors influence the way people vote, and political stances are closely related to moral foundations. While liberal voters are more focused on social justice, conservative voters have their focus set on economic stability. This is why economic appeals can be a great tool for convincing conservative voters. However, it really comes down to the individual, their economic incentives, and their willingness to listen to ideas outside of their conservative thinking box. If a conservative voter has their money tied up in the fossil fuel industry, an economic appeal probably won't convince them. But if the voter does not invest in the fossil fuel industry, and they genuinely want to know the best ways to improve the economy, then economic appeals can be an effective tool. [(go-to-url: "https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2020/november/conservatives-and-liberals-motivated-by-different-psychological-.html ")] NYU.The effectiveness of Motivational Interviewing (MI) has been shown to be similar to other, widely popular, therapy methods such as Dialetical or Cognitive Behavior Therapy (DBT or CBT). What differentiates MI from these other methods, is that it tends to reach this same level of effect at a much quicker pace. In general, patients treated with MI have a 10-20% improvement in positively changing their mindest and behavior when compared to patients undergoing no treatment. While the number of encounters necessary for MI to have its desired effect varies on a case-by-case basis, it requires about 101-180 minutes less overall time than other leading techniques. Even with this expedited treatment, changes made with MI have been shown to endure longer than a year in a majority of cases. Repeat MI treatments can prolong these positive changes by helping people restructure their mindset when the initial, unhealthy behavior and/or mentality begins to return. [[Click here to learn more about the Stages of Change.]] In the effort to support positive behavior changes to address climate change, think of MI as a tool for creating beneficial connections between you and a group or individual. This technique is largely based in making a genuine, human connection while speaking with someone so that you can support them choosing to make these healthy changes //themself.// The lasting nature of the behavior change is due to the restructuing of how the person thinks while you guide them through the process of making connections between their thoughts, choices, and the outside world. ''References:'' Lundahl, B. and Burke, B.L. (2009), (link: "The effectiveness and applicability of motivational interviewing: a practice-friendly review of four meta-analyses.")[(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.1002/jclp.20638")] J. Clin. (link:"Strategies for Clinical Discussions About Climate Change.")[(goto-url:"https://doi.org/10.7326/M20-6443")] Annals of Internal Medicine, 174(3), 417–418.In a study focused on the use of Motivational Interviewing (MI) to change behavior in regards to climate change, two different techniques are used to guide the process: the provision of information, and decisional balance. Providing information is broken down into more subcategories, which should help the interviewer avoid the common pitfall of just inundating someone with facts to make them change their mind. First, in the process of providing information, is the provision of basic information on the state of global warming. This basic information can include both scientific and non-scientific information. An example of each is: the trends in CO2 emissions and their correlation with global warming (scientific), and the motivation for the growing support of enacting policies addressing climate change (non-scientific). Setting the stage with basic information is then supported by normative information, which is information on social and moral norms related to global warming. These ‘norms’ should be specific to the person being interviewed, as the goal is for them to form internalized norms that motivate their behavior changes. An example of this would be informing someone of local initiatives to reduce litter as the trash has been linked to the growing number of deaths in a native animal species. This would be effective //if// the person you're speaking to is passionate about the well-being of animals. Given that people place different levels of importance in different topics, try to pick something that pertains to their specfici interests. Being unaware of their interests is expected, MI requires getting to know the other person so that you are able to effectively communicate with them. Ask general questions that pertain to the topic and you're likely to get better insight into their internal motivations and how you can connect that to them making positive changes to mindset and behavior. Decisional balance is an exercise of taking the interviewee through a decision-making process during your conversation. In this exercise, you help the person that you're speaking with weighs the short- and long-term costs and benefits, to both themselves and society, in them making the behavior change. The goal of this process is to help the interviewee develop a greater understanding of their behaviors with the intent of helping them develop an internal motivation for change. An example of this process would be guiding someone through the pros and cons to themselves and the environment for them to discontinue purchasing from ‘fast-fashion’ companies. (link: "What colour is the cloud?.")[(goto-url:"https://www.eib.org/en/stories/digital-footprint ")]The myth of the green cloud. European Investment Bank. Retrieved March 28, 2023.Though individuals themselves are not the main //sources// of GHG emissions, their habits play into //why// those emissions happen in the first place. Take meat production, for example. The production of meat accounts for nearly a third of global GHG emissions from food production. This represents around 17 billion metric tonnes of GHGs per year - more than double that of the entire US. Beef alone accounts for nearly a quarter. By reducing your meat consumption, you can slowly chip away at the overall problem. The average American eats about 260 pounds of meat (all types) in a year. That's about half a cow, 52 chickens, or just under 2 pigs. By reducing your consumption, you reduce the amount of livestock needed to meet demand. If //everyone// can reduce their consumption, we can make a serious dent in the amount of GHGs emitted globally. [[Explore Question #1 ->What is the best course of action that you can take as an individual?]] ''References:'' 1. Milman, O. (2021, September 13). (link: "Meat accounts for nearly 60% of all greenhouse gases from food production, study finds.")[(goto-url:"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2021/sep/13/meat-greenhouses-gases-food-production-study")]The Guardian. Retrieved March 28, 2023. 2. Kuck, G., &amp; Schnitkey, G. (2021, May 12). (link: "An overview of meat consumption in the United States.")[(goto-url:"https://farmdocdaily.illinois.edu/2021/05/an-overview-of-meat-consumption-in-the-united-states.html")] farmdoc daily. Retrieved March 28, 2023.Try to eat seasonally and locally. Not only will you get better tasting produce, you'll also reduce the distance that food has to travel, which in turn decreases the emissions produced during that travel. Smaller operations also tend to have higher biodiversity, which is better for the soil. You could also try to eat less animal products overall. The GHG emissions related to the production of fruits and vegetables are about 10-15 times lower than those related to animal products. [[Explore "Energy" -> Energy]] [[Explore "Clothing" -> Clothing]] [[Return to Question #1 ->What is the best course of action that you can take as an individual?]] [[Explore Question #2 ->Why should you try to be environmentally friendly if you're not the main issue?]] Try to get as much out of what you wear as possible. Sustainably produced clothing can be more expensive, so this might look like having a smaller wardrobe overall. You'll most likely pay more upfront for higher quality, sustainable clothing, but you'll get more out of it in the long run. Also, consider learning how to properly wash and repair your clothes to improve their longevity. If possible, shop second hand, especially for more expensive, but long-lasting items like a good pair of boots. [[Explore "Energy" -> Energy]] [[Explore "Food -> Food]] [[Return to Question #1 ->What is the best course of action that you can take as an individual?]] [[Explore Question #2 ->Why should you try to be environmentally friendly if you're not the main issue?]] There are the typical ways to save, such as lowering (or raising) your thermostat and taking shorter showers. But you should also consider your digital footprint. Energy consumed by the digital sector is growing by 9% per year and makes up around 4% of global GHG emissions. That's more than civil aviation! Try to find moments to reduce your data traffic and storage, and consider what electronics you //really// need. If you're spending a good chunk of money on a computer, consider a PC with components that you can swap out when needed, so you don't end up needing to buy a new one every few years. [[Explore "Clothing" -> Clothing]] [[Explore "Food" -> Food]] [[Return to Question #1 ->What is the best course of action that you can take as an individual?]] [[Explore Question #2 ->Why should you try to be environmentally friendly if you're not the main issue?]] Although it seems counterintuitive, more education makes Republicans more likely to not believe in human-made climate change. About 25% of Republicans with only a high school education say they are worried about climate change, but only 8% of Republicans with a college degree say the same. For Democrats, this statistic is flipped with a higher level of education correlating to a higher level of worry about climate change. The reason for this is mostly due to the fact that climate change is framed as mostly a political issue rather than a scientific one. Even though college-educated Republicans have more exposure to the scientific information around climate change, they also have more exposure to partisan messages about the issue, which end up having more of an impact. Climate change is a relatively new issue and it is very complicated. Instead of forming beliefs based on personal experience or religion, like many other hot topic issues, many people look to political elites to help guide their opinions. Conservative elites are deeply skeptical of climate change which leads to Republicans being skeptical as well. This is called a polarization effect. When political elites disagree their views tend to be adopted, first, by the highest educated members of each party. These people then become more divided as they find more information that confirms their viewpoint. The pattern of more education leading to more division between parties is not unique to climate change. Trust in the media as well as opinions on government run healthcare and taxes also diverge between the parties as education increases. (link:"Read more about the polarization effect here!") [(go-to-url:"https://www.simplypsychology.org/group-polarization.html")] ''Other References: '' Newport, F., & Dugan, A. (2015, March 26). (link:"College-Educated Republicans Most Skeptical of Global Warming.")[(go-to-url:"https://news.gallup.com/poll/182159/college-educated-republicans-skeptical-global-warming.aspx")] Gallup. Retrieved March 27, 2023, from https://news.gallup.com/poll/182159/college-educated-republicans-skeptical-global-warming.aspx Quealy, K. (2017, November 14). (link:"The More Education Republicans Have, the Less They Tend to Believe in Climate Change.")[(go-to-url:"https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/11/14/upshot/climate-change-by-education.html")] The New York Times. Retrieved March 27, 2023, from https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/11/14/upshot/climate-change-by-education.htmlDemocrats and Republicans are deeply divided on the issue of climate change. The divide is so deep it makes the drying up reserviors jealous! They disagree over whether it is happening, why it’s happening, and what actions to take to stop it. This division matters because it impacts what steps the government can and does take to help curb the impacts of climate change. The different parties have different views and thoughts on what to do about this issue which slows down forward progress towards stopping climate change. An example of this is the back and forth between former President Trump and President Biden. Trump pulled the United States out of the Paris Climate Agreement, an agreement between countries to make efforts to limit the global temperature rise. When Biden became president, he had the country rejoin the Paris Climate Agreement and also passed a bill giving hundreds of billion dollars to clean energy sources. The next president could reverse these efforts or a new Congress could make it impossible to pass legislation of any kind. This back and forth slows down any real actions the country can take to curb the effects of climate change. Having division on this critical issue in the public means the government elected will also be divided. Which means it is harder and slower to pass important regulations related to climate change. Retrieved March 27, 2023, from https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-54797743 Weise, E. (2023, February 17). (link:"Water crisis in West: Massive reservoir Lake Powell hits historic low water level.")[(go-to-url:"https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2023/02/17/lake-powell-water-level-drought-water-crisis-west/11257099002/ ")] USA Today. Retrieved May 1, 2023, from https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2023/02/17/lake-powell-water-level-drought-water-crisis-west/11257099002/Leaders in climate change comedy, like comedian David Perdue, tailor their climate change jokes toward specific groups in order to make them more effective. David Perdue is a black comic who makes jokes about race as part of his regular routine. He makes the issue of climate change seem more impactful to other black Americans by intertwining climate change jokes with race jokes. In one of his sets, Perdue says, “Solar power is free labor, and the most American thing to do is to use free labor. We just have to tell people the sun is Black.” This joke is somewhat irreverent and makes fun of America’s sordid history with race, but that is exactly what makes it more effective than ordinary climate change activism. Americans who feel threatened by “wokeness” respond better to jokes that slap the idea of political correctness in the face. Comedians who can wield that technique with a hint of subtlety, like Perdue, can frame their jokes to make even “anti-woke” Americans begin changing their views in spite of themselves. Michelle Wolf is another comedian who uses pointed comedy to promote climate activism. Rather than framing her jokes through the lens of race, she frames through the lens of relationship drama. One of Wolf’s jokes in her HBO special goes, “Mother Nature is trying to kill us in the most passive-aggressive way possible. She’s like, ‘What? I raised the temperature a little.” This implicitly relates climate change to the age-old problem of domestic partners who can’t agree on an ideal A/C setting. In doing so, Wolf suggests that the anger and indignation that we feel as victims of domestic passive aggression should be directed toward combating climate change: let’s fight global warming like we’re an old married couple! Wolf and Perdue highlight how comedians in this area liken climate change to historical phenomena or everyday life to harness the strong emotions and personal connection that people have toward more tangible aspects of their lives and direct those feelings toward climate change. Such an approach is critical because a 2014 study from Yale University shows that 70% of the U.S. population that is relatively unconcerned with climate change does not pay attention to climate change information. Thus, it falls to groups like comedians to weave such information into the everyday lives of those otherwise unconcerned with it. ''References'' 1.
